{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636503"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:29:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:29:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17582"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17582"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.1,0.75,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71454"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10272"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56963"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10090"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24123"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71454"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin A is an essential fat-soluble vitamin required for vision, immune function, and cell growth and is absorbed in the digestive tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its absorption?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absorbed directly into portal circulation","Absorbed primarily in the stomach","Requires an active sodium-dependent transporter","Requires dietary fat and bile salts for absorption","Requires intrinsic factor for absorption"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin A \u003Cstrong\u003Erequires dietary fat and bile salts for absorption\u003C/strong\u003E. Bile salts are necessary for the formation of micelles that solubilise vitamin A, allowing it to be absorbed by enterocytes. Once absorbed, vitamin A is packaged into chylomicrons and transported via lymphatics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsorbed directly into portal circulation\u003C/strong\u003E - As a fat-soluble vitamin, vitamin A is incorporated into chylomicrons and transported via lymphatics\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires an active sodium-dependent transporter\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes glucose absorption, not vitamin A absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsorbed primarily in the stomach\u003C/strong\u003E - Vitamin A is absorbed in the small intestine, not the stomach\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires intrinsic factor for absorption\u003C/strong\u003E - Intrinsic factor is required for vitamin B12 absorption, not vitamin A\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter absorption, vitamin A is stored primarily in the liver as retinyl palmitate and is released bound to retinol-binding protein as needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin A (retinol) is absorbed in the small intestine and requires dietary fat for optimal absorption.","Vitamin A is stored primarily in the liver as retinyl palmitate.","Vitamin A absorption requires bile salts for micelle formation and incorporation into chylomicrons."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Available from: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56963"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17582"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56963"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T17:26:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T17:27:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10272"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71454"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T